ased","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1452–1506":"1452–1506","about 1492":"about 1492","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","1540":"1540","1506":"1506","about 1483":"about 1483","Furness, Lancashire, England":"Furness, Lancashire, England","Graythwaite, Cumberland,, England":"Graythwaite, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Hawksfieldshead Hawkshead, Lancashire,, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Esthwaite Hall, Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Curwen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place called Culewen (now Colvend) in Kirkcudbrightshire. The family was early established in Lancashire, where it was often pronounced without the <i>-w-</i>; see   Corrin   and   Currin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corrin","meanings":["Irish and Manx: shortened form of <i>Mac Torin</i>, from Gaelic <i>mac</i> ‘son (of)’ + Old Norse <i>Thórfinnr</i> (from <i>Thórr</i>, the name of the Scandinavian thunder god, + the ethnic designation <i>Finnr</i>). Compare   Turpin  . This name has occasionally been confused with   Corin  .","English (Lancashire): variant of   Curwen  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Curwen was born in 1469, in Furness, Lancashire, England, her father, Garrat Curwen, was 29 and her mother, Margaret Dickinson, was 17. She married George Sandys about 1483, in Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1493, in her hometown, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1469–1493":"1469–1493","1465–1513":"1465–1513","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1492–Male":"1492–Surnud","1493–1540":"1493–1540","1493–Male":"1493–Surnud","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1452–1506":"1452–1506","about 1492":"umbes 1492","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","1540":"1540","1506":"1506","about 1483":"umbes 1483","Furness, Lancashire, England":"Furness, Lancashire, England","Graythwaite, Cumberland,, England":"Graythwaite, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hawksfieldshead Hawkshead, Lancashire,, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Esthwaite Hall, Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1469–1493":"1469–1493","1465–1513":"1465–1513","1490–Male":"1490–Kuollut","1492–Male":"1492–Kuollut","1493–1540":"1493–1540","1493–Male":"1493–Kuollut","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1452–1506":"1452–1506","about 1492":"noin 1492","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","1452":"1452","1540":"1540","1506":"1506","about 1483":"noin 1483","Furness, Lancashire, England":"Furness, Lancashire, England","Graythwaite, Cumberland,, England":"Graythwaite, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hawksfieldshead Hawkshead, Lancashire,, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Esthwaite Hall, Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1469–1493":"1469–1493","1465–1513":"1465–1513","1490–Male":"1490–Décédé","1492–Male":"1492–Décédé","1493–1540":"1493–1540","1493–Male":"1493–Décédé","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1452–1506":"1452–1506","about 1492":"environ 1492","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1465":"1465","14